SIMPLE: summon
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Summon
<hw>Sum"mon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Summoned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Summoning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>somonen</ets>, OF. <ets>sumundre</ets>, <ets>semondre</ets>, F.
<ets>semondre</ets>, from (assumed) LL. <ets>summon⟦ecr⟧re</ets>, for L.
<ets>summon⟦emac⟧re</ets> to give a hint; <ets>sub</ets> under +
<ets>monere</ets> to admonish, to warn. See <er>Monition</er>, and cf.
<er>Submonish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To call, bid, or cite; to
notify to come to appear; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stiffen the sinews, <qex>summon</qex> up the blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trumpets <qex>summon</qex> him to war.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give notice to, or command to appear, as in
court; to cite by authority; <as>as, to <ex>summon</ex>
witnesses</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To call upon to surrender, as a
fort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To call; cite; notify; convene; convoke; excite;
invite; bid. See <er>Call</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Summoner</ent>⟦br⟧
